Executive '''oversight of [[United States]] [[covert operations]]''' has been carried out by a series of sub-committees of the [[United States National Security Council|National Security Council]] (NSC).
==Birth of covert operations in the Cold War== At the beginning of the [[Cold War]], it was not inevitable that covert operations would become the dominion of the [[Central Intelligence Agency]] (CIA).{{sfn|Corke|2006|pages=102–104}} The [[National Security Act of 1947]] did not explicitly authorize the CIA to conduct covert operations, although Section 102(d)(5) was sufficiently vague to permit abuse.{{sfn|Prados|2006|page=[https://books.google.no/books?id=3OCDelYICIsC&pg=PA35 35]}}<ref>{{cite web|last=Houston|first=Lawrence R.|editor=[[Office of the Historian]]|title=CIA Authority to Perform Propaganda and Commando Type Functions|url=https://history.state.gov/historicaldocuments/frus1945-50Intel/d241|website=history.state.gov|language=en|date=25 September 1947}}</ref> At the very first meetings of the NSC in late 1947, the perceived necessity to "stem the flow of communism" in [[Western Europe]]—particularly [[Italy]]—by overt and covert "psychological warfare" forced the issue.{{sfn|Corke|2006|pages=102–104}} The actual responsibility for these operations was a hot potato, and when it was decided that the [[United States Department of State|State Department]] would be in charge, [[United States Secretary of State|Secretary of State]] [[George Marshall]] sharply opposed it, fearing it would tarnish the international credibility of his department. The upshot was that responsibility for covert operations was passed on to the CIA; this was codified in a NSC [[National security directive#Truman and Eisenhower administrations|policy paper]] called NSC{{nbsp}}4-A,<ref name="NSC 4-A">{{cite web|author=[[Foreign Relations of the United States (book series)|FRUS]]|title=NSC 4-A – National Security Council Directive to Director of Central Intelligence Hillenkoetter|url=https://history.state.gov/historicaldocuments/frus1945-50Intel/d257|website=history.state.gov}}</ref> approved in December 1947.{{sfn|Corke|2006|pages=102–104}} NSC{{nbsp}}4-A provided the authorization for the intervention of the CIA in the [[Italian general election, 1948|Italian elections of April 1948]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Mitrovich|first=Gregory|title=Undermining the Kremlin: America's Strategy to Subvert the Soviet Bloc, 1947-1956|date=2000|publisher=Cornell University Press|isbn=0801437113|page=[https://books.google.no/books?id=w6TVdT-q7vcC&pg=PA17 17]}}</ref>
===Proposed NSC 4-A Panel=== A draft<ref>{{cite web|author=[[Foreign Relations of the United States (book series)|FRUS]]|title=NSC 4-A – Draft Directive to Director of Central Intelligence Hillenkoetter|url=https://history.state.gov/historicaldocuments/frus1945-50Intel/d253|website=history.state.gov}}</ref> of NSC{{nbsp}}4-A envisioned the creation of a NSC-designated "panel" to approve operations. The executive secretary of the NSC, [[Sidney Souers]], recommended that the panel be composed of representatives from the departments of State, [[United States Department of the Army|Army]], [[United States Department of the Navy|Navy]] and [[United States Department of the Navy|Air Force]], as well an "observer" representative from the [[Joint Chiefs of Staff]].<ref>{{cite web|author=[[Foreign Relations of the United States (book series)|FRUS]]|title=Memorandum From the Executive Secretary (Souers) to the National Security Council|url=https://history.state.gov/historicaldocuments/frus1945-50Intel/d255|website=history.state.gov|date=16 December 1947}}</ref> This provision was dropped in the final version, which simply stated that the [[Director of Central Intelligence]] (DCI) "is charged with ensuring that [covert] psychological operations are consistent with U.S. foreign policy and overt foreign information activities, and that appropriate agencies of the U.S. Government, [...], are kept informed of such operations which will directly affect them."<ref name="NSC 4-A"/> ==From NSC 10/2 to NSC 5412 (June 1948–March 1955)== According to the [[Church Committee]], throughout the period June 1948 to March 1955, "NSC directives provided for consultation with representatives of State and Defense". But "these representatives had no approval function. There was no formal procedure or committee to consider and approve projects."<ref>{{cite web|author=[[Church Committee]]|title=Final Report, Book I|date=26 April 1976|url=https://archive.org/details/pdfy-UM4X5C4pdvn8FqLd|page=[https://archive.org/stream/pdfy-UM4X5C4pdvn8FqLd#page/n59/mode/2up 49]}}</ref> ===NSC 10/2 Panel=== The arrangement in NSC{{nbsp}}4-A did not please the influential [[Director of Policy Planning|director]] of the State Department's [[Policy Planning Staff (United States)|Policy Planning Staff]] (S/P), [[George F. Kennan]].{{sfn|Corke|2006|pages=108–109}} Under his leadership, a S/P paper titled "The inauguration of organized political warfare"<ref>{{cite web|title=The inauguration of organized political warfare.|url=https://history.state.gov/historicaldocuments/frus1945-50Intel/d269|website=history.state.gov|language=en|date=4 May 1948}}</ref> was circulated in the NSC in early May 1948, which said that "there are two major types of political warfare—one overt and the other covert. Both, from their basic nature, should be directed and coordinated by the Department of State." Yet Kennan wanted to have his cake and eat it too: the paper made it clear that the State Department should not be formally associated with the conduct of covert operations.{{sfn|Corke|2006|pages=108–109}} Then the [[Joint Chiefs of Staff]] entered the fray by guarding its prerogatives, particularly in wartime, especially in theatres of war.{{sfn|Lilly|1951|pages=[https://archive.org/stream/THEDEVELOPMENTOFAMERICANPSYCHOLOGICALOPERATIONS1945-1951BYEDWARDPLILLYRDP86B00269R000900020001-9#page/n43/mode/2up 45–47]}} As a result of the controversy spurred by Kennan, NSC{{nbsp}}4-A was replaced by NSC{{nbsp}}10/2,<ref name="NSC 10/2">{{cite web|author=[[Foreign Relations of the United States (book series)|FRUS]]|title=NSC 10/2 – National Security Council Directive on Office of Special Projects|url=https://history.state.gov/historicaldocuments/frus1945-50Intel/d292|website=history.state.gov}}</ref> approved by President [[Harry Truman]] on 18 June 1948, creating the [[Office of Policy Coordination]] (OPC). Kennan was still not satisfied and continued to press for State control, hoping that his choice for OPC director, [[Frank Wisner]], would be loyal to the State Department—he was not.{{sfn|Corke|2006|pages=111–112}}
NSC{{nbsp}}10/2 was the first presidential document which specified a mechanism to approve and manage covert operations, and also the first in which the term "covert operations" was defined.{{sfn|Prados|2006|pages=[https://books.google.no/books?id=3OCDelYICIsC&pg=PA40 40–41]}} NSC{{nbsp}}10/2 charged the DCI with "Ensuring, through designated representatives of the Secretary of State and of the Secretary of Defense, that covert operations are planned and conducted in a manner consistent with US foreign and military policies and with overt activities."<ref name="NSC 10/2"/> The representatives to this "10/2 Panel", also known as the "OPC Consultants",{{sfn|Gustafson|2012|page=149}} were Kennan for State (1948–1950) and [[Joseph McNarney]] for Defense (1948–1949).{{sfn|Karalekas|1976|pages=[https://archive.org/stream/finalreportofsel04unit#page/34/mode/2up 34–35]}} The panel, which met about once a week, was supplanted from January 1950 on by the regular attendance of a representative from the Joint Chiefs of Staff.{{sfn|Lilly|1951|page=[https://archive.org/stream/THEDEVELOPMENTOFAMERICANPSYCHOLOGICALOPERATIONS1945-1951BYEDWARDPLILLYRDP86B00269R000900020001-9#page/n87/mode/2up 89]}} According to Anne Karalekas, a [[Church Committee]] staffer, it did not constrain the OPC:
{{Quote|[The 10/2 Panel was] not an approval body, and there was no formal mechanism whereby individual projects had to be brought before [it] for discussion. Because it was assumed that covert action would be exceptional, strict provisions for specific project authorization were not considered necessary. With minimal supervision from State and Defense and with a shared agreement on the nature of the OPC mission, individuals in OPC could take the initiative in conceiving and implementing projects.{{sfn|Karalekas|1976|pages=[https://archive.org/stream/finalreportofsel04unit#page/34/mode/2up 34–35]}}}}
In the first half of its existence, OPC was not really under CIA's control. In the words of [[Edward P. Lilly]], DCI [[Roscoe H. Hillenkoetter]], "although authorized by NSC-10/2 to supervise OPC, had allowed OPC to go its own way." OPC was brought under CIA control in October 1950, when [[Walter Bedell Smith]] became DCI.{{sfn|Lilly|1951|page=[https://archive.org/stream/THEDEVELOPMENTOFAMERICANPSYCHOLOGICALOPERATIONS1945-1951BYEDWARDPLILLYRDP86B00269R000900020001-9#page/n89/mode/1up 90]}} OPC was merged on 1 August 1952 with the CIA branch responsible for [[espionage]], the Office of Special Operations (OSO), to form the [[Directorate of Plans]] (DDP).
===NSC 10/5 Panel=== Truman swelled the bureaucracy on 4 April 1951 when he established the [[Psychological Strategy Board]] (PSB). DCI Smith, seeking more high-level policy guidance, wanted the PSB "to replace the 10/2 Panel as approval body";{{sfn|Prados|2006|page=[https://books.google.no/books?id=3OCDelYICIsC&pg=PA81 81]}} this proposal was adopted by the NSC.{{sfn|Karalekas|1976|pages=[https://archive.org/stream/finalreportofsel04unit#page/34/mode/2up 34–35]}} NSC{{nbsp}}10/5<ref>{{cite web|author=[[Foreign Relations of the United States (book series)|FRUS]]|title=NSC 10/5 – SCOPE AND PACE OF COVERT OPERATIONS|url=https://history.state.gov/historicaldocuments/frus1950-55Intel/d90|website=history.state.gov}}</ref> tried to specify the purpose of the PSB. The 10/2{{nbsp}}Panel, which continued to function,<ref>{{cite web|last=Allen|first=Raymond B.|authorlink=Raymond B. Allen|title=Procedure for Handling 10/5 Matters in PSB|url=https://history.state.gov/historicaldocuments/frus1950-55Intel/d104|website=history.state.gov|language=en|date=20 February 1952}}</ref> was replaced in February 1952 by an enlarged 10/5{{nbsp}}Panel, which also included PSB staff.<ref>{{cite web|first=C. Tracy|last=Barnes|authorlink=Tracy Barnes|title=BRIEFING TO THE PSYCHOLOGICAL STRATEGY BOARD ON SOME 10/5 PROBLEMS|url=https://history.state.gov/historicaldocuments/frus1950-55Intel/d108|website=history.state.gov|language=en|date=7 May 1952}}</ref> According to an internal CIA review from 1967, the 10/5{{nbsp}}Panel "functioned much as the 10/2 Panel had, but the resulting procedures proved cumbersome and potentially insecure."<ref name=CIA1967>{{cite web|author=[[CIA]]|title=Secret appendix C to the Katzenbach Committee's report – COORDINATION AND POLICY APPROVAL OF COVERT OPERATIONS|date=23 February 1967|url=https://history.state.gov/historicaldocuments/frus1964-68v33/d263}}</ref>
According to John Prados, the CIA cut the PSB out of the loop, establishing instead an internal mechanism for approval of operations.{{sfn|Prados|2006|pages=[https://books.google.no/books?id=3OCDelYICIsC&pg=PA80 80–82]}} In 1953, DCI Smith said that the PSB was "incompetent and its work irrelevant".{{sfn|Gustafson|2012|page=155}}
"As the Truman administration ended", writes the [[Office of the Historian]],
{{Quote|CIA was near the peak of its independence and authority in the field of covert action. Although CIA continued to seek and receive advice on specific projects from the NSC, the PSB, and the departmental representatives originally delegated to advise OPC, no group or officer outside of the DCI and the President himself had authority to order, approve, manage, or curtail operations.<ref name=FRUS_note/>}}
===Enter Eisenhower=== The [[Eisenhower administration]] took office on 20 January 1953. When Eisenhower replaced the PSB with the [[Operations Coordinating Board]] (OCB) on 2 September 1953, he also did away with the 10/5{{nbsp}}Panel, reverting to "a smaller group identical to the former 10/2{{nbsp}}Panel, without OCB staff participation."<ref name=CIA1967/> On 15 March 1954, Eisenhower approved NSC{{nbsp}}5412,<ref>{{cite web|author=[[Foreign Relations of the United States (book series)|FRUS]]|title=NSC 5412 – NATIONAL SECURITY COUNCIL DIRECTIVE ON COVERT OPERATIONS|url=https://history.state.gov/historicaldocuments/frus1950-55Intel/d171|website=history.state.gov}}</ref> which required CIA to consult with OCB.<ref name=CIA1967/> Although Eisenhower would later congratulate the CIA with [[1954 Guatemalan coup d'état|its success in deposing]] [[Guatemala]]'s democratically elected President, [[Jacobo Árbenz]], he was privately irked by CIA's unauthorized bombing of [[SS Springfjord|SS ''Springfjord'']]. According to Prados, that incident "convinced Eisenhower of the need for more rigorous control over covert action".{{sfn|Prados|2006|pages=[https://books.google.no/books?id=3OCDelYICIsC&pg=PA148 148], [https://books.google.no/books?id=3OCDelYICIsC&pg=PA121 121] (quoted)}}
==Planning Coordination Group (March 1955–December 1955)== The arrangement in NSC{{nbsp}}5412 suffered the same problem as the 10/5{{nbsp}}Panel;<ref name=CIA1967/> OCB "included more officials than ought to be concerned with secret war."{{sfn|Prados|2006|page=[https://books.google.no/books?id=3OCDelYICIsC&pg=PA150 150]}} So on 12 March 1955, Eisenhower approved NSC{{nbsp}}5412/1,<ref>{{cite web|author=[[Foreign Relations of the United States (book series)|FRUS]]|title=NSC 5412/1 – Covert Operations|url=https://history.state.gov/historicaldocuments/frus1950-55Intel/d212|website=history.state.gov}}</ref> creating a more senior Planning Coordination Group (PCG) within OCB. Significantly, the directive explicitly charged PCG with ''approving'' covert operations.<ref name=Church50>{{cite web|author=[[Church Committee]]|title=Final Report, Book I|date=26 April 1976|url=https://archive.org/details/pdfy-UM4X5C4pdvn8FqLd|pages=[https://archive.org/stream/pdfy-UM4X5C4pdvn8FqLd#page/n61/mode/2up 50–51]}}</ref> The PCG proved to be a failure; its chairman, [[Nelson Rockefeller]], recommended the abolishment of PCG before year's end.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rockefeller|first1=Nelson|authorlink1=Nelson Rockefeller|title=Report of the Planning Coordination Group|url=https://history.state.gov/historicaldocuments/frus1950-55Intel/d246|language=en|date=14 December 1955|work=Planning Coordinating Group}}</ref> According to Prados, the problem was that CIA had not been forthcoming with details, latching on to a mention of "need-to-know" in NSC{{nbsp}}5412/1. The next directive would solve this by creating a committee "so high-powered there could be no question" of its need to know.{{sfn|Prados|2006|page=[https://books.google.no/books?id=3OCDelYICIsC&pg=PA150 150]}}
==Special Group/303 Committee (December 1955–February 1970)== NSC{{nbsp}}5412/2<ref name="NSC 5412/2">{{cite web|author=[[Foreign Relations of the United States (book series)|FRUS]]|title=NSC 5412/2 – Covert Operations|url=https://history.state.gov/historicaldocuments/frus1950-55Intel/d250|website=history.state.gov}}</ref> was approved by Eisenhower on 28 December 1955, a directive which remained in force for 15 years.<ref name=Church50/> Paragraph 7 specified the new oversight mechanism:
{{Quote|Except as the President otherwise directs, designated representatives of the Secretary of State and of the Secretary of Defense of the rank of [[Assistant Secretary#United States|Assistant Secretary]] or above, and a representative of the President designated for this purpose, shall hereafter be advised in advance of major covert programs initiated by CIA under this policy or as otherwise directed, and shall be the normal channel for giving policy approval for such programs as well as for securing coordination of support therefor among the Departments of State and Defense and the CIA.<ref name="NSC 5412/2"/>}}
The resulting body became known as the '''5412 Committee''' or, from 1957, the '''Special Group'''.{{sfn|Jackson|1973|page=[https://archive.org/stream/HistoryOfAllenWelshDullesAsCIADirectorVolumeIIICovertActivities#page/n165/mode/2up 162]}}{{refn|group=note|It had many similar designations. For example: '''Special Group 5412''', '''5412 Group''' and '''Special NSC 5412/2 Group'''.}} It was the first time a "designated representative" of the President was included in the process;<ref name=Church50/> Eisenhower used his [[National Security Advisor (United States)|National Security Advisors]] for this purpose.{{sfn|Jackson|1973|page=[https://archive.org/stream/HistoryOfAllenWelshDullesAsCIADirectorVolumeIIICovertActivities#page/n81/mode/2up 78]}} The DCI was an ''ex officio'' member.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Daugherty|first1=William|title=Executive Secrets: Covert Action and the Presidency|date=2004|publisher=University Press of Kentucky|isbn=0813123348|page=[https://books.google.no/books?id=4NgTQuw8uUEC&pg=PA136 136]|language=en}}</ref> In 1957, Eisenhower made the [[Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff|Chairman]] of the [[Joint Chiefs of Staff]] a member as well.{{sfn|Prados|2006|page=[https://books.google.no/books?id=3OCDelYICIsC&pg=PA182 182]}} In practice the membership of the Special Group varied on an ''ad hoc'' basis.{{sfn|Karalekas|1976|page=[https://archive.org/stream/finalreportofsel04unit#page/50/mode/2up 51]}}<ref name=FRUS_note>{{cite web|title=Note on U.S. Covert Actions|url=https://history.state.gov/historicaldocuments/frus1964-68v12/actionsstatement|website=history.state.gov|language=en}}</ref>
In late 1956, the newly formed [[PBCFIA]], which had turned a candid eye towards covert operations, took issue with the "very informal" procedures of the Special Group.<ref>{{cite web|work=[[Studies in Intelligence]]|publisher=[[Central Intelligence Agency]]|date=Summer 1969|title=The President's Board: 1956–1960, Overseeing the intelligence community|first=Philip K.|last=Edwards|page=126|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/readingroom/document/cia-rdp89b00980r000400120002-6}}</ref>{{sfn|Prados|2006|pages=[https://books.google.no/books?id=3OCDelYICIsC&pg=PA160 160–161]}} Consequently, an annex<ref>For the text of the annex: {{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/MemoonCovertOperationsbyJPatrickCoynecovops|title=Covert Operations|date=9 May 1961|first=J. Patrick|last=Coyne|work=[[President's Foreign Intelligence Advisory Board]]|pages=[https://archive.org/stream/MemoonCovertOperationsbyJPatrickCoynecovops#page/n13/mode/2up 14–15]}}</ref> to NSC{{nbsp}}5412/2 was approved by Eisenhower on 26 March 1957, clarifying project approvals, and for the first time requiring the CIA to circulate "proposal papers" in advance of approval.{{sfn|Prados|2006|pages=[https://books.google.no/books?id=3OCDelYICIsC&pg=PA160 160–161]}} The board continued to press for more prominence to the Special Group to keep the CIA from freewheeling. Eisenhower himself saw the proper functioning of the Special Group as crucial to fend off initiatives for meaningful congressional oversight of covert operations.{{sfn|Prados|2006|pages=[https://books.google.no/books?id=3OCDelYICIsC&pg=PA180 180–182]. For Eisenhower's views on congressional oversight, see pp. [https://books.google.no/books?id=3OCDelYICIsC&pg=PA182 182], [https://books.google.no/books?id=3OCDelYICIsC&pg=PA151 151–152]}} On 26 December 1958 Eisenhower asked the Special Group to institute weekly meetings,{{sfn|Prados|2006|page=[https://books.google.no/books?id=3OCDelYICIsC&pg=PA182 182]}} with the result that "criteria for submission of projects to the Group were, in practice, considerably broadened."<ref>{{cite web|author=[[Church Committee]]|title=Final Report, Book I|date=26 April 1976|url=https://archive.org/details/pdfy-UM4X5C4pdvn8FqLd|page=[https://archive.org/stream/pdfy-UM4X5C4pdvn8FqLd#page/n63/mode/2up 52]}}</ref>
===Kennedy administration=== The Special Group fell by the wayside when new administration of [[John F. Kennedy]] took office on 20 January 1961; although it remained "in theory intact", in practice it "took a backseat to meetings at which JFK personally presided".{{sfn|Prados|2006|page=[https://books.google.no/books?id=3OCDelYICIsC&pg=PA241 241]}}{{refn|group=note|Some sources actually claim the Special Group was disbanded at this time.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Daugherty|first1=William|title=Executive Secrets: Covert Action and the Presidency|date=2004|publisher=University Press of Kentucky|isbn=0813123348|pages=[https://books.google.no/books?id=4NgTQuw8uUEC&pg=PA151 151ff]|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Friedman|first1=Rebecca R.|title=Crisis Management at the Dead Center: The 1960-1961 Presidential Transition and the Bay of Pigs Fiasco|journal=Presidential Studies Quarterly|date=17 March 2011|volume=41|issue=2|page=324|doi=10.1111/j.1741-5705.2011.03856.x|issn=0360-4918}}</ref>}} After the failed [[Bay of Pigs Invasion]], the Special Group returned to prominence,<ref>{{cite web|author=[[Church Committee]]|title=Final Report, Book I|date=26 April 1976|url=https://archive.org/details/pdfy-UM4X5C4pdvn8FqLd|page=[https://archive.org/stream/pdfy-UM4X5C4pdvn8FqLd#page/n63/mode/2up 52]}}</ref> and new procedures were set out in July 1961.{{sfn|Jackson|1973|page=[https://archive.org/stream/HistoryOfAllenWelshDullesAsCIADirectorVolumeIIICovertActivities#page/n83/mode/2up 81]}} In the wake of the scandal, [[Deputy Director for Plans|DDP]] [[Richard M. Bissell Jr.]] suggested the name and workings of the Special Group be made public to demonstrate to the American people that the CIA was under effective executive oversight; that did not happen.{{sfn|Prados|2006|page=[https://books.google.no/books?id=3OCDelYICIsC&pg=PA241 375]}}
A second '''Special Group (Augmented)''' existed from November 1961 to the [[Cuban Missile Crisis]] of October 1962.<ref name=FRUS_note/> The only difference was that it was specifically dedicated to managing the [[Cuban Project]] which sought to overthrow [[Fidel Castro]]'s regime, and was headed by [[United States Attorney General|Attorney General]] [[Robert Kennedy]].{{sfn|Prados|2006|page=[https://books.google.no/books?id=3OCDelYICIsC&pg=PA286 286]}} After the Missile Crisis brought the world to the brink of destruction, management of the war against Castro was transferred to discussions in the [[EXCOMM]] and NSC proper, before being handed over to an "obscure NSC appendage" known as the '''Standing Group''' chaired by [[National Security Advisor (United States)|National Security Advisor]] [[McGeorge Bundy]].{{sfn|Prados|2006|page=[https://books.google.no/books?id=3OCDelYICIsC&pg=PA313 313]}}
===Johnson administration=== The Special Group was renamed to the '''303 Committee''' on 2 June 1964, in response to the publication of the book ''The Invisible Government'' by [[David Wise (journalist)|David Wise]] and Thomas B. Ross, which made the old name public.<ref>{{cite web|author=[[Church Committee]]|title=Final Report, Book I|date=26 April 1976|url=https://archive.org/details/pdfy-UM4X5C4pdvn8FqLd|page=[https://archive.org/stream/pdfy-UM4X5C4pdvn8FqLd#page/n63/mode/2up 53n19]}}</ref> A NSC staffer had recommended the new name be "something utterly drab and innocuous" to deflect away attention.<ref name=Jessup>{{cite web|first=Peter|last=Jessup|title=Proposed Name Change for Special Group (5412)|url=https://history.state.gov/historicaldocuments/frus1964-68v33/d203|date=19 May 1964|work=[[United States National Security Council|National Security Council]]}}</ref> The number refers to the [[national security directive]] which effected the change, [[National Security Directive|NSAM]]{{nbsp}}303.<ref name=Jessup/><ref>{{cite web|title=NSAM 303|date=2 June 1964|website=discoverlbj.org|url=https://www.discoverlbj.org/item/nsf-nsam303}}</ref>
==40 Committee== On 17 February 1970, President [[Richard Nixon]] approved [[National Security Decision Memorandum|NSDM]]{{nbsp}}40,<ref>{{cite web |title=National Security Decision Memoranda 40 |url=https://fas.org/irp/offdocs/nsdm-nixon/nsdm-40.pdf |website=fas.org}}</ref> superseding and revoking NSC{{nbsp}}5412/2, and replacing the 303 Committee with the 40 Committee. Among the few substantive changes introduced by Nixon was the inclusion of Attorney General [[John N. Mitchell]] and a requirement to review covert programs annually.{{sfn|Prados|2006|pages=[https://books.google.no/books?id=3OCDelYICIsC&pg=PA385 385–387]}} Like earlier, public exposure was the motive for changing the name; National Security Adviser [[Henry Kissinger]] explained to Nixon that "In view of recent mention of the 303 Committee in the public media, the directive changes the committee name to coincide with the number assigned to the NSDM itself, which is 40."<ref>{{cite web|author=Henry Kissinger|authorlink=Henry Kissinger|title=Responsibility for the Conduct, Supervision and Coordination of Covert Action Operations|date=16 February 1970|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/readingroom/docs/LOC-HAK-513-1-1-9.pdf#page=3}}</ref>
Nixon and Kissinger, who was charged with overseeing all covert operations on Nixon's behalf,{{sfn|Prados|2006|page=[https://books.google.no/books?id=3OCDelYICIsC&pg=PA382 382]}} kept the 40 Committee out of the loop on almost all the major and sensitive decisions, and the 40 Committee stopped having meetings; in 1972 it only met once.{{sfn|Prados|2006|pages=[https://books.google.no/books?id=3OCDelYICIsC&pg=PA385 385–387]}}
==Operations Advisory Group== On February 18, 1976, 40 committee was replaced by the '''Operations Advisory Group''', in accordance with [[Executive Order 11905]] issued by [[Gerald Ford]]. The new group was composed of the [[National Security Advisor (United States)|President's Assistant for National Security Affairs]], the Secretaries of [[United States Secretary of State|State]] and [[United States Secretary of Defense|Defense]], the [[Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff]], and the [[Director of Central Intelligence]].<ref name="state.gov">{{cite web|url=https://fpc.state.gov/documents/organization/39313.pdf|format=PDF|title=Proposals for Intelligence Reorganization, 1949-2004|publisher=[[United States Department of State]]}}</ref>
==NSC Special Coordination Committee== The following year, on May 13, 1977, President [[Jimmy Carter]] issued Executive Order 11985 which updated the previous order, and renamed the Operations Advisory Group to the '''NSC Special Coordination Committee''' (SCC).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fas.org/irp/offdocs/eo/eo-11985.htm|title=Executive Order 11985|date=May 13, 1977|publisher=Federation of American Scientists}}</ref>
==National Security Planning Group== Under the Reagan administration, the Special Coordination Committee was replaced by the '''National Security Planning Group''' (NSPG) which included the Vice-President, the Secretary of Defense, the Secretary of State, the Assistant for National Security Affairs, and the Director of the CIA.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Covert Action and Accountability: Decision-Making for America's Secret Foreign Policy |author=Loch K. Johnson|journal=International Studies Quarterly|date=March 1989|jstor=2600495}}</ref> One level below the NSPG was the Policy Coordination Group (PCG), first known as the Crisis Pre-Planning Group (CPPG); one source describes the PCG as the actual successor to the Special Coordination Committee.{{sfn|Prados|2006|page=[https://books.google.no/books?id=3OCDelYICIsC&pg=PA496 496]}}
==Special Intelligence Office== In 2002–2003, during the [[George W Bush|Bush Administration]], [[Under Secretary of Defense for Policy]] [[Douglas Feith]] created a special-purpose group encompassing and focusing on all military and intelligence efforts involving [[Iraq]], [[Afghanistan]], and other [[Near East|Near East countries]], as well as all activities falling under the rubric of the [[Global War on Terror]]. This group has been said to have been responsible for [[stovepiping]] selective raw intelligence data, bypassing [[intelligence analysis|analysis processes]] as well as bypassing customary cooperation and coordination with [[NSA]], [[Mossad]], and other intelligence entities in order to shape decisions as to the war with Iraq. Its functions were morphed in the [[Office of Special Plans]], which was subsequently investigated for manipulations of intelligence, unlawful activities, and [[espionage]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2003/jan/30/iraq.alqaida |title=Al-Qaida and Iraq: how strong is the evidence? |author=Julian Borger in Washington, Richard Norton-Taylor and Michael Howard |publisher=The Guardian |date=30 January 2003}}</ref>
